Galathea inconspicua
belongs to the group of species with uninterrupted gastric ridges on the carapace, the carapace lateral margin armed with one small but distinct spine between the anterolateral spine and the anteriormost branchial marginal spine, the antennular basal article only with two well-developed terminal spines and the extremely narrow rostrum ( 2.5–3.5 times longer than broad). This group contains six closely related species, including five new species:
G. ganindo
n. sp.
from the Philippines to New Caledonia ,
G. inconspicua
from Indonesia to New Caledonia ,
G. perone
n. sp.
from the Philippines ,
G. rhaphidia
n. sp.
from Fiji and Tonga ,
G. scolopia
n. sp.
from Papua New Guinea and Vanuatu ,
G. tribulosa
n. sp.
from the Solomon Islands . These species can be distinguished from one another by the following characters:
